Package com.shouldis.bitset

Class BitSet

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.shouldis.bitset.BitSet
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    ConcurrentBitSet
    public class BitSet
extends java.lang.Object
    Represents a fixed number of bits stored within an internal integer array, mapping positive integer indices to individual bits and facilitating the manipulation of those individual bits or ranges of bits, as well as retrieving their boolean values. Using this memory structure, this class allows grouping of multiple bitwise operations into fewer operations on the underlying integer words.

    The bits represented by this BitSet will either be in the live state (1, true), or the dead state (0, false).

    BitSet on its own is thread-safe only for read operations, although a BitSpliterator may be used to stream indices in an order and grouping appropriate for parallel manipulation of bits. Alternatively, a ConcurrentBitSet may be used to make all operations thread-safe, requiring no external synchronization at the cost of performance.

    If size isn't a multiple of WORD_SIZE, there will be "hanging" bits that exist on the end of the last integer within words, which are not accounted for by size. No exception will be thrown when these bit indices are manipulated or read, and in aggregating functions (population(), hashCode(), etc.), any hanging bits will have their effect on those functions made consistent by cleanLastWord().

    Otherwise, accessing a negative index, or any index greater than or equal to size will cause an IndexOutOfBoundsException to be thrown.

    Author:
    Aaron Shouldis
